DEMONSTRATORS
DECRIED
(ACP) — Campus demand
senators who discuss speeches
and district employment interviews are “wholly incompatible
with the basic tennis of a great
university," University of Michigan president Robberl meeting
told Michigan State University
graduates at fall announcement. the MSU State News reported.
For years, meeting said, universities have fought against
restrictions on speakers and on
many computer the fight has
been won.
“How are we to explain,” he
asked, "that while all kinds of
speakers may come to the
campus, some of them Will be
so discussed that their views
may not be heard?”
Some argue, and with merit,
meeting said, that employment
interviews are not an integral
part of campus life and therefore should be conducted off
campus.
“instruction tactics, however, are not directed at all interventions but only at selected
entertaining,” he said.
“Others, he said, resolve the
problem by incoming a ‘higher
mobility’ to determine who
should he allowed to interview.
"The trouble With this concept
is that it is not at all Clear
who is to be in charge of judy:
ing the pictures of a higher
mobility," meeting said.
He said the demonstration
fail to recognize the nature or
the recruiting process — that a
student who signs up for an interview does so as an “exercise of individual judgment.”
